speakers.shortBio: Manasi Joshi is a Director of Software Engineering at Google.
speakers.name: Manasi Joshi
speakers.title: Director of Software Engineering
speakers.bio: Director of Software Engineering, Google Manasi Joshi is a Director of Software Engineering at Google. She leads the Machine Learning Productivity efforts as part of Research/Google Brain team. She and her team focus on making ML modeling pipelines highly efficient and partner with modelers to ensure that the models are reliable and scalable. She collaborates closely with teams in Research as well as non Research product engagement efforts including parts of Google Cloud. Prior to founding and leading the ML Productivity team, Manasi led teams in the Display Ads Infrastructure Product Area at Google with a focus on improving engineering productivity across product landscapes. Her focus was on developing Serving Infra and Ads Privacy for over 10 years. Manasi is driven by fairness and advocacy in AI and in the workplace. She served on the Ads Diversity Council for 3 years prior to moving to Google Research Team and is currently pioneering the ML fairness efforts in her current team. Manasi earned her Masters in Computer Science from the University of Minnesota (Go Gophers) and joined Google in 2005. Manasi was born and raised in Pune

SANDEEP GUPTA is a Product Manager for TensorFlow at Google, where he helps develop and drive the roadmap for TensorFlow (Google’s open-source library and framework for machine learning) for supporting machine learning applications and research. His current focus is on TensorFlow’s 2.0 release, improving TensorFlow’s usability and driving adoption in the community and enterprise, and on TensorFlow.js - a library bringing Machine Learning to JavaScript developers. Sandeep is excited about how Machine Learning and AI are transforming our lives in a wide variety of ways, and works with the Google team and external partners to help create powerful, scalable solutions for all.   Prior to joining Google, Sandeep was the technology leader for advanced imaging and analytics research and development at GE Global Research with specific emphasis on medical imaging and healthcare analytics.

speakers.name: Bruce Schwack
speakers.title: Co-Founder and Director of Communications
speakers.bio: Bruce Schwack is Director of Communications for Netmeds.com, India’s largest licensed e-pharmacy where he oversees the firm's communications and it’s multi-channel customer interactions, and participates in development of the companies ad campaigns and TVC's. He has worked with Netmeds CEO and Founder Pradeep Dadha for many years as they built a global marketing and logistics company, and in 2015 he helped to launch Netmeds.  His aim is to inspire and motivate each of member of the team, and to instill the importance and true meaning of customer “service.” His plan is to keep growing personally and transferring his knowledge and understanding of “behavior economics”, and to deploy emerging machine learning  and AI, not to replace Netmeds’ employees, but to help them be more efficient,  while assuring that Netmeds maintains brand leadership in the emerging “epharma” space.   He’s an avid fitness enthusiast and travel aficionado and plays golf and visit jungle habitats wherever he goes. He loves to spend his free time with his pups, Layla and Majnun and can be regularly seen enjoying Marina Beach.  Bruce is actively involved in social causes as well and is associated with the Love Care Centre, an orphanage in Kancheepuram.

speakers.title: Obsessive Dictator
speakers.bio: Kumar Rangarajan is one of the co-founders of Slang Labs, a platform that enables companies to integrate voice augmented experiences (VAX) to their apps  Kumar envisions a future where users are able to get things done in their apps, by just talking to it, in the language of their choice.   Prior to starting Slang Labs, Kumar had founded Little Eye Labs which was acquired by Facebook in the year 2014. This acquisition also made Little Eye Labs the first Indian start-up to be acquired by Facebook. Post this acquisition, Kumar joined Facebook’s headquarters in the United States where he worked for 3 years before returning to India to start Slang Labs.   Kumar has a rich IT background and has held engineering and leadership positions at various companies.   His larger goal is to make the internet more accessible and engaging for the user.

items.description: Functional Programming(FP) has become the all the rage at the moment. Maybe you have been wanting to have a look at it but haven't or you already have given it a go but got scared away with all the FP jargon (We are looking at you Monads). In this talk, we will look at how to get started with FP using Kotlin with the existing knowledge you have and look at how we can start moving towards FP by making a few changes(trust me, no talking about the jargon or 3rd party libraries) in your day to day activities. I will also talk about my journey about going from OOP to FP. We will look at some of the mistakes I did and some of the approaches I took while learning FP. We will also create a simple structured approach to start learning/implementing FP in your existing code so that you can learn by doing. We will see real life practical examples of implementing FP in your Android project by converting a few samples from OOP to FP. At the end of the talk we will look at why a library like Arrow-KT can be useful once you have mastered the basics of FP and also how to approach Arrow-KT for your FP needs.

items.title: Building Equitable Tech
items.description: It is our responsibility as technologists to understand the societal implications of emerging tech including how we can combat algorithm bias, collect data more responsibility, and build inclusive AI. We just don’t use technology anymore, we live it and it has deep impacts on various levels , from individual ,society ,nations and humans. We will talk about frameworks & toolkits which we use to facilitate us having these conversations and looking at software delivery from Equitable tech perspective.

items.title: The road to the google cloud native
items.description: What does it take to move a consumer-facing business serving millions of consumers every day to public cloud? How does one choose Google Cloud over its competitors? How can Google Cloud native technologies be leveraged to build a data platform with 100+ TB of data? How is leveraging the public cloud to serve consumers in emerging markets different from serving those in first world markets? What are the advantages and pitfalls of being early adopters of technology such as Google Cloud Dataflow, BigQuery, ML Engine, Datastore, Spanner, Cloud Functions, AutoML etc?
